spanGrp.span: They came from the other side, from a place called Talamanca.
Jie-wa (_) beteũ-lo rö kã' etawa kã' kie Talamanka
When they came here, the place was not like we see it today;
Jie-wa beteũ-lo jie-wa (_) deu-lo jiwa-ra nã ka rö ka kã' rö (_) jibi se je të sũẽ-gẽ unã
it was full of trees and rivers.
kã' rö kalwa jebö diglö-wa jebö
When they came to live here everything our elders did they… they… lived and did what they had to do; they practiced their culture.

Jie-wa deu-lo se-nã' jie-wa jie-wa të todo jirö jirö wẽ-gẽ esteee se se sigeglö-wa të ra nã je wã-nẽ Jie-wa jie-wa të jie-wa wã jie-wa deu-lo jiwa jie-wa se-nã' jie-wa të jirö kianã' wa-nã (_) jie-wa rö jie-wa të jie-wa kultura wẽ-gẽ
They told us how they got here.
Jie-wa të se je ĩã se je ĩã í wã' mẽnẽbi (m) (_) ĩã í shá mẽnẽbi (_) jie-wa deu-lo jiwa ra
Our clan is from that place called Talamanca.
Jie-wa/ se je ditsö rö jamĩ kã' kie-gẽ Talamanka [*wa ra nã]
They know that we have to do all that.
(_) jie-wa jue-nã'-ra-nã se je nã (_) todo je je wã'
Thus nowadays they tell us that we have to do what they did because they say that when they came here they practiced their various customs.

je kueinga ĩã jir se ĩã í yer-gẽ-nã se të je wẽ porke jie-wa deu-lo Jie-wa të í pa-gẽ-nã jie-wa deu-lo jiwa (_) jie-wa rö jie-wa jirö tsõ jaulë jaulë je praktikawẽ se je të Je kueinga nã jir (_) se ĩã í yir-gẽ-nã se ĩã se të je wẽ-ra-nã (_) böi rö
That’s why today they tell us that when they came here uh this place was not like we see it today.
Atara nã estee jie-wa deu-lo jiwa ra ji kã rö ka kã' rö jibi se je të sũẽ-gẽ kunã
Everything they did originally has to be done nowadays.
Taranã (_) kẽr (_) jie-wa të je (_) jirda (_) jie-wa të todo jirö jirö wẽ-gẽ (_) a (_) siga-wa të sögötö je wẽ-gẽ-ite jira
They speak our language; thay want us to tell the things they did and that we should not be ashamed today.

Aser/ jie-wa rö jie-wa të (_) estee (_) ktö she-gẽ jie-wa inga kianã'-nã jirö wẽ jirö jirö wã' jie-wa të jirö wẽ-gẽ jie-wa të jie-wa jie-wa ktö jie-wa je (_) je she se je të ke se je öinã je yiga je kueinga nã jir
When they came we had not been born; but they want… they planted bananas, manioc; they did not know the things that exist today.

jie-wa deu-lo-ra-nã se/ sa sa ka kõr-pa sa jirö ka/ (m) tarana ji sa tsõ-nẽ jeranã sa inga/ jie-wa inga í kianã' (_) jie-wa deu-lo-ra jie-wa të jie-wa të jirö kuö bi chomõ bi shkö bi tubie-gẽ jie-wa sẽr-gẽ je mẽ Jie-wa ka wã jirö rö sũ-lë jirö tsõ jirda ka sũ-lë jie-wa wã je ra
Jira se je wã jirö sũ-lë kable je sũ-lë se je wã (_)
Their houses were not like today’s houses;
Je kueinga jie-wa deu-lo-ra jie-wa jie-wa jũ ka rö (_) jũ bi kunã
they were made of wood and grass.
Jie-wa jũ rö kal wa sökku wa
They did not have the houses we have.
Se je se je të she/ se je wã ji bi jũ tsõ ka ta ji/ ka ta je ki/ je kã' ska (_)
They did not now the food from today either.
Jie-wa ka wã jirö (_) jirö se je/ ñã-nã tsõ jira ka ka sũ-lë
They planted and they made their houses themselves when they got here.
jie-wa/ je je s/ jera jie wakwa/ (_) je je í wakwa të jirö töbie-gẽ jie wakwa jũ yuwö-gẽ
They made their things themselves, as they were poor and had no money.
Jie wakwa deu-lo-ra jie wakwa je wã jirö/ jie wakwa jirö tsõ rö (_) ka je ka je/ (_) jie-wa ra jie-wa ka pobre wã nãglö ta ka jirö ta
Detsí yue-gẽ rö í wakwa të
they made chicha, which is our drink; they also made dray-banana drink and beverage from corn on the cob.
Jera jie-wa (_) jie-wa të (_) (_) dí wẽ-gẽ je nẽ rö se je se je esteee (_) ya-nã rö (_) tú jamẽ bokol
They always cought fish and ate them with bananas and stuff.
Siempre jie-wa të nĩmã guge-gẽ-ra-nã jie-wa të je wẽ-gẽ rö chomõ ra jirö ra
Nowaydays it is not like that;
Je ta jira ka je je ta ĩã (_) jira
we now eat only good things.
se je të jirö böi bönẽ ñẽ-gẽ rö
